<F P=100> INTER-AFRICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CFA Summit Continues; Debate Held on Compensation </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Backup' Measures Noted </H4>
<F P=102> AB1101212094 Paris AFP in French 2103 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1101212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Dakar, 11 Jan (AFP) -- The CFA franc was devalued by 
50 percent, it was announced this evening in Dakar by the 14 
member countries of the franc zone. 
  The devaluation allows for a series of backup measures which 
were not immediately published. The decision was published 
after an extraordinary summit was carried out behind closed 
doors yesterday and today including representatives of 14 member 
countries of the franc zone (10 heads of state, three prime 
ministers, and a minister of finance from 14 African countries). 

</TEXT>

