<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Kenya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moi Meets High-Level Economic Delegation From Japan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA1301171394 Nairobi Kenya Broadcasting Corporation Network 
in English 1000 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA1301171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nairobi Kenya Broadcasting Corporation Network 
in English 1000 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] His Excellency President Daniel arap Moi today at 
State House, Nairobi, received a high-level Japanese economic 
and technical delegation. The leader of the delegation, Mr. 
Masao Sawaki, informed President Moi that Japan would increase 
its funding of specific projects to Kenya by 50 percent in the 
next five years. Mr. Sawaki said Japan placed Kenya in high 
esteem, especially due to her rapid development. This, he said, 
was the reason the delegation came to reappraise its support for 
Kenya's development. 
  President Moi thanked the government and people of Japan for 
their enormous contribution to Kenya's development since 
independence. He added that, because of this support, Kenya 
regarded Japan as a true friend and partner in development and, 
noting that he was committed to environmental conservation as it 
guaranteed the success of future development efforts, the 
president said he would appreciate assistance to construct 
several dams in the country. 
  He informed the Japanese delegation that Kenya's rapid 
development was mainly due to the uninterrupted peace since 
independence and the participation of wananchi [citizens] in the 
harambee [communal fund-raising] self-help strategy. President 
Moi said he attached great importance to security and added that 
the issue would be given the attention it deserved. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

