<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   De Klerk Appeals for White Help in Black Municipal Services </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2001142194 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1150 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2001142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Johannesburg Jan 20 SAPA -- President F W de Klerk 
on Thursday [20 January] made a tacit plea to white urban local 
authorities to contribute in redressing the decades-long neglect 
and abuse of black municipal services. Speaking at the local 
government conference at the World Trade Centre outside 
Johannesburg, Mr de Klerk said the end of township rent and 
services boycotts would help pay the R[rand]1.8 billion township 
services debt. It would also impact enormously on the cash flow 
of local authorities. "But it is a matter of debate whether 
that will be enough to redress the legacy of the past. I do not 
think so." 
  It was accepted that the financing and implementation of 
upgrading local services would require regional and national 
support. Something more would be needed, however, and many 
local authorities would be in a position to make substantial 
contributions. "For the sake of peace and stability I believe 
they should do so." 

</TEXT>

