<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Justice Minister, PAC Holding Talks in Pretoria </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2001145294 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1400 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2001145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Defense has confirmed that Minister 
Kobie Coetsee is engaged in talks with a PAC [Pan-Africanist 
Congress] delegation in Pretoria. Earlier the PAC said that 
members of its Executive Committee, including Mr. Benny 
Alexander and Mr. Barney Desai, were to have talks with the 
government today. The talks follow the PAC's announcement that 
it has suspended its armed struggle. The agenda for today's 
talks is expected to include possible amnesty for APLA [Azanian 
People's Liberation Army -- PAC military wing] members, joint 
command of the security forces, and PAC participation in the 
Transitional Executive Council. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-43944 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr014_c_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-014 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Progress' Reported in Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2101084294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 2359 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB2101084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria Jan 20 SAPA -- Progress was reportedly made 
in Pretoria on Thursday to bring the Pan Africanist Congress 
[PAC] back into the transition process. In talks, the government 
and the PAC agreed to establish three working committees to meet 
as early as next week to take further Thursday's "exploratory 
meeting". 
  A possible first meeting between President F W de Klerk and 
PAC leader Clarence Makwetu was also raised "and may be taken 
further", a government spokesman said afterwards. 
  The two sides met for two hours at the offices of government 
chief negotiator Roelf Meyer. The issues discussed were: 
  -- whether there should be one or two ballot papers on April 
27. The PAC, like the Freedom Alliance, wants one for the 
national government and one for the provincial government; 
  -- amnesty for members of the PAC's armed wing, the Azanian 
Peoples Liberation Army, in the wake of the PAC's suspension of 
its armed struggle; 
  -- the PAC's participation in the Transitional Executive 
Council. The PAC announced it would join the body only if there 
was joint control over all the country's armed forces; and 
  -- the PAC's participation on the executive council 
sub-council on defence. Some executive council participants have 
argued that PAC representation on the sub-council would meet its 
demand for proper joint control over the armed forces. 
  The government's Departments of Defence, Justice and 
Constitutional Development will together with PAC representation 
form the three working committees. "The most important thing we 
want to discuss with government is the question of one ballot or 
two ballots," PAC negotiator Gora Ebrahim told SAPA. 
  The PAC had consistently favoured two ballots, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

