<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNITA Reportedly Presents Views on Police Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB1901193394 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB1901193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Lusaka talks are still covering specific issues 
of the national police force. Blondin Beye and the observers 
today met with the National Union for the Total Independence of 
Angola [UNITA]. The government did not take part in the meeting 
and is not aware of the outcome of the meeting. Pedro Manuel 
reports from Lusaka: 
  There are contradictory reports about the new text dealing 
with specific issues. Yesterday the mediator and the observers 
were reported to have drafted a new document. Meanwhile, 
reliable sources say the mediator and the observers failed to 
put the final touches on the new document because UNITA did not 
cooperate. UNITA successively postponed its comments on the 
specific principles ruling the police force, alleging that it 
needed more time to evaluate the main document. Finally, this 
afternoon the UNITA negotiating team presented its position to 
the mediator and the observers, but it has not been possible to 
confirm this in view of the news blackout [preceding word in 
English]. 
  Meanwhile, the government is awaiting for Blondin Beye to 
give details about this afternoon's meeting between the 
mediator, the observers and UNITA. There are rumors that 
government and UNITA delegations will meet face to face tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

