<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Renamo Leader Says Continued Peace Depends on Funds </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2001172294 Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio in English 
1600 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2001172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Channel Africa Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mozambique's opposition Renamo [Mozambique National 
Resistance] leader Afonso Dhlakama says he hopes to secure 
financial support when he visits the United Nations secretary 
general, Dr. Butrus Butrus-Ghali, next month. Last Friday Mr. 
Dhlakama met the UN special envoy to Mozambique, Mr. Aldo 
Ajello, about raising funds to help Renamo to transform itself 
into a political party. Mr. Ajello said although he had 
appealed to the international community for support there had 
been little response beyond the 6 million dollars pledged by 
Italy early last year. Mr. Dhlakama said the international 
community promised him millions of dollars before he signed the 
Mozambican Peace Accord and that continued peace depended on 
having sufficient funds. 

</TEXT>

