<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Mozambique </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Infantry Battalion To Begin Training in Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB2001200294 Maputo Radio Maputo in English 1800 GMT 20 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> MB2001200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Maputo Radio Maputo </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The starting date for the training of Mozambique's 
infantry battalion involving Renamo [Mozambique National 
Resistance] and government troops is now scheduled for the first 
week in February. The announcement was made by UN Operation 
Deputy Force Commander Brigadier Anisur Rahman following 
yesterday's meeting in Maputo of the Joint Commission charged 
with setting up the new army. 
  This date represents a new delay under the time table signed 
by the government, Renamo, and the UN last October. The 
training should have started this month. The 540 military 
instructors and [word indistinct] trained in Zimbabwe last year 
have returned to Mozambique. 
  Brig. Rahman said the government and Renamo will name the 
members who are going to be part of the country's military high 
command in 8 days' time from today. Both sides are reported to 
have already selected representatives for the high command. 
  The two sides also agreed on the insignia for the new army, 
on the criteria for the selection of troops who will be trained 
as special forces, and on norms for moving troops from assembly 
points where they are currently gathering, to the training 
centers. 

</TEXT>

