<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Renewed Shooting Reported in Southern Brazzaville </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB1901135594 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 1230 GMT 19 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB1901135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The situation in Congo is extremely tense. Sporadic 
shooting from heavy artillery and bursts of automatic machinegun 
fire were heard this morning in the southern district of 
Brazzaville, especially at Bacongo and Makelekele districts, 
which have been sealed off for the past three days by government 
forces. Armored cars have been deployed at Makelekele district 
over the past three days in an attempt to prevent new clashes 
between the opposition coalition militia and government forces. 
These clashes have claimed about 75 lives in southern 
Brazzaville since mid- December. 
  The cordoning off of Bacongo is the result of the kidnapping 
of Lieutenant Jonathan Mabiala, an officer of the presidential 
security, who has still not been found. The presidential 
security has accused the private militia of opposition leader 
Bernard Kolelas of carrying out the kidnapping. The opposition 
has denied any involvement in this affair. 
  Meanwhile, about 100 armed supporters of the presidential 
group gathered around the seat of the ruling party, the 
Pan-African Union for Social Democracy this morning. They are 
demanding their integration into the Army. According to 
witnesses, the police did not intervene. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

