<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Somalia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Freed Detainees Address Rally, Praise Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA2001200794 (Clandestine) Radio Mogadishu Voice of the 
Great Somali People in Somali 1700 GMT 20 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA2001200794 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Mogadishu Voice of the 
Great Somali People </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Somali </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Osman Hassan Ali, alias Osman Ato, a member of 
the United Somali Congress [USC] central committee, speaking on 
behalf of the eight citizens detained by UN Operation Somalia 
[UNOSOM] after being illegally kidnapped from their homes, today 
addressed thousands of jovial people at 1 July Independence 
Square. The demonstrators carried placards and the flag of the 
Republic of Somalia, and chanted: "Down with Somalia's enemies" 
"UNOSOM leave Somalia", "may the agreement to unite Somalia 
succeed" and other slogans. 
  The rally was first addressed by Awil Ahmad Abdi, from the 
Somali Democratic Movement and Mohamed Ahmad Nur, the USC 
secretary for reconstruction and rehabilitation, who greeted and 
congratulated the Somali citizens that UNOSOM had illegally 
kidnapped from their homes. They also congratulated the Somali 
National Alliance supporters, particularly those from Mogadishu 
and its surrounding environs, who had been holding non-stop 
demonstrations which, they said, finally forced UNOSOM to 
release the officials they had illegally detained. 
  Speaking on behalf of the eight citizens, Osman Hassan Ali 
thanked the Somali people and said that history would not forget 
those people involved in the struggle against the UNOSOM troops. 
Osman Hassan Ali said that they had done something which had 
been lacking in Somalia and the African continent, and that this 
had sent a clear signal to foreigners that they could not do 
whatever they wished to an independent country and people. 
Referring to the agreement reached between brother Somalis and 
signed at the Kah Hotel in Mogadishu, he said he strongly 
supported it, pointing out that the agreement was the key for 
peace and stability to come about in Somalia. In conclusion, he 
appealed to the Somali people to show tolerance, fortitude, and 
mutual respect for each other's rights. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

